ecords/chanel9617 ''CHANEL9617''].</ref>\n|-\n|\"Submarines\"\n|[[DJ Fresh|Fresh]]\n|\"Submarines\" CD single<ref>[[DJ Fresh|Fresh]] (19 July 2004). \"Submarines\" (liner notes). [[Breakbeat Kaos]], [http://www.rolldabeats.com/release/breakbeat_kaos/bbk004 ''BBK004''].</ref>\n|-\n|\"Pack of Wolves\"\n|[[Zentveld & Oomen|Nightbreed]]\n|\"Pack of Wolves\" CD [[maxi single]]<ref>[[Zentveld & Oomen|Nightbreed]] (27 September 2004). \"Pack of Wolves\" (liner notes). [[Ram Records (UK)|Ram Records]], [http://www.rolldabeats.com/release/ram_records/ramm52cd ''RAMM52CD''].</ref>\n|-\n|\"Bacteria\"\n|[[Ed Rush]] & [[Optical (artist)|Optical]]\n|''The Remixes Vol. 2'' single<ref>[[Ed Rush]] & [[Optical (artist)|Optical]] (8 November 2004). ''The Remixes Vol. 2'' (liner notes). Virus Recordings, [http://www.rolldabeats.com/release/virus_recordings/vrs014b ''VRS014B''].</ref>\n|-\n|2005\n| \"[[Just a Ride]]\" <small>([[Adam F]] & Pendulum music mix)</small>\n|[[Jem (singer)|Jem]]\n| \"Just a Ride\" CD maxi single<ref>[[Jem (singer)|Jem]] (13 June 2005). \"[[Just a Ride]]\" (liner notes). Crazy Wise Music, [http://www.rolldabeats.com/release/crazy_wise_music/crazy03 ''CRAZY03''].</ref>\n|-\n|2010\n|\"[[Stay Too Long]]\"\n|[[Plan B (British musician)|Plan B]]\n|\"Stay Too Long\" single<ref>[[Plan B (British musician)|Plan B]] (11 January 2010). \"[[Stay Too Long]]\". [[679 Recordings]] / [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]], [http://www.discogs.com/Plan-B-Stay-Too-Long/master/215437 ''679L171''].</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin}}\n'''General'''\n* [http://www.rolldabeats.com/artist/pendulum/ Pendulum]. ''rolldabeats''. Retrieved on 22 September 2008.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100723155725/http://www.pendulum.com/about/discography.htm The full Pendulum discography]. [[Pendulum (drum and bass band)|Pendulum]]. [https://www.webcitation.org/5bB6dVGM4?url=http://www.pendulum.com/discography.htm Archived] on 28 September 2008.\n'''Specific'''\n{{Refend}}\n{{Reflist|20em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.pendulum.com/ Official website]\n* [{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p183189|pure_url=yes}} Pendulum] at [[Allmusic]]\n* [http://www.discogs.com/artist/Pendulum+(3) Pendulum] at [[Discogs]]\n\n{{Pendulum}}\n{{featured list}}\n\n[[Category:Pendulum (drum and bass band)|Discography]]\n[[Category:Discographies of Australian artists]]\n[[Category:Rock music group discographies]]\n[[Category:Electronic music discographies]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox artist discography\n|Artist = [[Pendulum (drum and bass band)|Pendulum]]\n|Image = Pendulum Live Electric 2007.jpg\n|Caption = Pendulum live at the [[Electric Ballroom]] in London during their 2007 tour.\n|Studio = 3\n|Compilation = 1\n|Live = 1\n|Singles = 24\n|Music videos = 12\n|Option = 36\n|Option name = Other appearances\n}}\n\n[[Pendulum (drum and bass band)|Pendulum]] are an Australian [[drum and bass]] band originating from [[Perth, Western Australia|Perth]], [[Western Australia]]. They have released three [[studio album]]s, one [[live album]], one [[Compilation album|compilation]], twenty-four [[single (music)|singles]] and twelve [[music videos]].\n\nPendulum were formed in 2002 by [[Rob Swire]], Gareth McGrillen and Paul \"El Hornet\" Harding in Perth.<ref name=about>[http://www.pendulum.com/about.htm Pendulum's history]. [[Pendulum (drum and bass band)|Pendulum]]. [https://www.webcitation.org/5bBELWLLs?url=http://www.pendulum.com/about.htm Archived] on 28 September 2008.</ref> Their first individual single release was the [[double A-side]] \"[[Spiral / Ulterior Motive|Spiral\" / \"Ulterior Motive]]\" in July 2003.<ref name=discog>[http://www.rolldabeats.com/artist/pendulum/releases/sort_by_year/asc Pendulum (releases, by year)]. ''rolldabeats''. Retrieved on 22 September 2008.</ref> The single was only released in [[New Zealand]] and did not receive much publicity, but later that year their track \"Vault\" was met with widespread underground recognition.<ref>[http://www.mp3.com/albums/20154937/summary.html Pendulum \u2013 ''In Silico'']. [[MP3.com]]. Retrieved on 25 November 2008. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081019091914/http://www.mp3.com/albums/20154937/summary.html |date=19 October 2008 }}</ref> Soon after the band relocated to the United Kingdom, where they were joined by guitarist [[Peredur ap Gwynedd]], [[Drum kit|drummer]] [[Paul Kodish]], and [[MC]] [[Ben Mount|Ben \"the Verse\" Mount]].<ref name=about/>\n\nTheir first full-length release followed in July 2005 with the album ''[[Hold Your Colour]]''.<ref name=discog/> Five singles were produced from the album, including \"[[Slam / Out Here|Slam\" / \"Out Here]]\", the first single by Pendulum to reach the top forty in the [[UK Singles Chart]].<ref name=ukcharts>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/31894/pendulum/|title=Pendulum {{!}} full Official Chart history|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref> In addition, two non-album singles were released. The first was Pendulum's remix of \"[[Voodoo People / Out of Space|Voodoo People]]\" originally by [[The Prodigy]], released on 3 October 2005. It reached number twenty in the UK charts and was the band's most successful single for almost three years.<ref name=ukcharts /> This was followed by \"[[Blood Sugar / Axle Grinder|Blood Sugar\" / \"Axle Grinder]]\", released on 18 June 2007, which was later appended to the reissue of ''Hold Your Colour'' due to its popularity.<ref name=discog/>\n\nPendulum's second album, ''[[In Silico (Pendulum album)|In Silico]]'', was released in May 2008 to significant commercial success.<ref name=discog/> The album charted at number two in the United Kingdom and at number nine in Australia,<ref name=ukcharts/><ref name=aucharts>Peaks in Australia:\n* All except noted: [http://www.australian-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Pendulum Discography Pendulum]. ''australian-charts.com''. Retrieved on 22 September 2008.\n* ''Hold Your Colour'': {{cite journal|url=http://pandora.nla.gov.au/pan/23790/20060220-0000/issue830.pdf|title=ARIA Report: Week Commencing 30 January 2008|issue=830|format=PDF|publisher=[[Australian Recording Industry Association]]|date=30 January 2008|accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref> and has been certified Platinum in the UK.<ref name=cert>[http://www.bpi.co.uk/certifiedawards/Search.aspx BPI certified awards search] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110511120001/http://www.bpi.co.uk/certifiedawards/search.aspx |date=11 May 2011 }}. [[British Phonographic Industry]] (5 February 2008 for ''In Silico'' and 28 May 2010 for ''Immersion''). Retrieved on 12 July 2010.</ref> Four singles have been released from ''In Silico''. The most successful of these is \"[[Propane Nightmares]]\", which reached number nine in the UK Singles Chart and was nominated for Best Single at the [[Kerrang!]] Awards 2008 ceremony.<ref name=ukcharts/><ref>[http://angryape.com/news/2008/07/23/kerrang-awards-2008-nominations-announced Kerrang! Awards 2008 nominations announced] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081007114404/http://angryape.com/news/2008/07/23/kerrang-awards-2008-nominations-announced |date=7 October 2008 }}. ''AngryApe'' (23 July 2008). Retrieved 28 September 2008.</ref>\n\nThe band's third album titled ''[[Immersion (album)|Immersion]]'' was released on 24 May 2010.<ref name=discog/> It peaked at number one in the United Kingdom during its first week of release, marking the band's success.<ref name=ukcharts/> The lead single from the album \"[[Watercolour (Pendulum song)|Watercolour]]\" reached number four on the UK Singles Chart, making it Pendulum's highest charting single to date.<ref name=ukcharts/> So far, ''Immersion'' has been their most successful album, based on the album sales, and the success of the first two singles at breaching the top thirty in the UK Singles Chart.\n\n==Albums==\n\n=